  1. Use the range of the latitude and longitude to build an appropriate bounding box for your map.
grizzly %>% 
  select(latitude, longitude) %>% 
  summary()
##     latitude       longitude     
##  Min.   :55.02   Min.   :-166.2  
##  1st Qu.:58.13   1st Qu.:-154.2  
##  Median :60.97   Median :-151.0  
##  Mean   :61.41   Mean   :-149.1  
##  3rd Qu.:64.13   3rd Qu.:-145.6  
##  Max.   :70.37   Max.   :-131.3
grizzly_lat <- c(55.01, 70.37)
grizzly_long <- c(-166.2, -131.3)
grizzly_bbox <- make_bbox(grizzly_long, grizzly_lat, f = 0.05)
  1. Load a map from stadiamaps in a stamen_terrain projection and display the map. Hint: use zoom=5.
grizzly_map <- get_stadiamap(grizzly_bbox, maptype = "stamen_terrain", zoom=5)
##   Stadia Maps  Stamen Design  OpenMapTiles  OpenStreetMap contributors.
ggmap(grizzly_map)

  1. Build a final map that overlays the recorded observations of grizzly bears in Alaska.
ggmap(grizzly_map) + 
  geom_point(data = grizzly, aes(longitude, latitude), size=0.4) +
  labs(x= "Longitude", y= "Latitude", title="Grizzly Bear Locations")
